    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-06-24T01:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-06-24T01:00:00-05:00" n="224"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d224">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">961.53/6–2454: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 224<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Republic of China (<persName
                            corresp="#p_RKL1" type="from">Rankin</persName>) to the <gloss type="to"
                            >Department of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret<lb/>priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Taipei</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-06-24T15:00:00+09:00"
                            >June 24, 1954—3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>711. <gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 702.<note n="1" xml:id="d224fn1">
                        <ref target="#d222">Document 222</ref>.</note> Two Chinese destroyer escorts
                    at 8 a.m. local time June 23 stopped and boarded Soviet tanker <hi rend="italic"
                        >Tuapse</hi> midway <pb facs="0512" n="484" xml:id="pg_484"/> between Luzon
                    and Formosa. After tanker crew sitdown strike of several hours vessel was
                    brought into Kaohsiung 7 a.m. June 24.</p>
                <p>Second Soviet tanker <hi rend="italic">Leningrad</hi> identified off coast
                    Indochina following same course as <hi rend="italic">Tuapse</hi>.</p>
                <p>Chinese Navy awaiting arrival <hi rend="italic">Leningrad</hi> and expects take
                    over vessel late afternoon June 25.</p>
                <p>Chinese Foreign Minister <persName corresp="#p_YGKCYK1">Yeh</persName> informs me
                    he opposed any seizure Soviet vessels on high seas and his view had concurrence
                    Chief Staff General <persName corresp="#p_CCJ1">Chou Chi-jou</persName>.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RKL1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rankin</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
